<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="chi-square-test-summary-5-1">
  <title>Chi-square Test Summary</title>

  <p>The chi-squared framework in this section uses one common structure across different study designs.</p>

  <assemblage>
    <title>Core Setup</title>
    <p><alert>Statistic:</alert> <m>\chi^2 = \sum \frac{(O-E)^2}{E}</m></p>
    <p><alert>Degrees of freedom:</alert> <m>(r-1)(c-1)</m></p>
    <p><alert>Direction of evidence:</alert> larger chi-squared values provide stronger evidence against <m>H_0</m>.</p>
    <p><alert>Expected count formula:</alert> <m>E = \frac{(\text{row total})(\text{column total})}{\text{table total}}</m></p>
    <p><alert>Technical conditions:</alert> at least 80% of expected counts are at least 5, and all expected counts are at least 1.</p>
  </assemblage>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Design-Specific Interpretation</title>
    <p><alert>Homogeneity setting:</alert> multiple populations or treatment groups are compared on one categorical response variable.</p>
    <p><m>H_0</m>: the population distributions are the same across groups.</p>
    <p><m>H_a</m>: at least one group distribution differs.</p>

    <p><alert>Association setting:</alert> one random sample is cross-classified by two categorical variables.</p>
    <p><m>H_0</m>: no population association between variables.</p>
    <p><m>H_a</m>: there is a population association.</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <p>After computing the p-value, examine the largest cell contributions or residuals to describe where observed counts differ most from expected counts.</p>
</section>
